snippet.textDisplay: I’m really confused. Like, did no one see the musical? It’s just a random fun, nonsensical jumble. The plot was minimal, the songs random, the cats more about aesthetic and stereotypes than well rounded characters. There was no way the movie was going to ever be anything but insane. The biggest mistake was in the marketing and them ever trying to make the movie serious. Cats the musical is a giant gymnastics filled theater kid fever dream. And it should never try to be anything else. It’s not for most people. It’s for musical nerds. And it’s proud of that. Whoever made the movie just didn’t get that memo I guess.

snippet.textDisplay: this does come from someone who probably has never even seen the stage production of cats. it's not the movie's fault at all. the original Broadway stage production tells the same story with the same songs. and does it all in one freaking dumpster. How can someone even go see Cats and treat it like it's an original musical written for film and not a well-known musical whose story was available for anyone who wished to know if the movie was something they would like to see or not? I've seen a lot of reviews for Cats, and most of the negative ones come from people that are NOT into musicals. People who didn't like Phantom, Wicked, Cats, Anything Goes, Rocky Horror, West Side Story and others. People that maybe can't say they disliked said musicals because they haven't ever even heard them. It's really simple. I wouldn't walk into a horror movie expecting to like it if I'm wasn't someone who's interested in horror movies in general. Especially if I didn't even like the trailer of said movie. But I guess some people just like to rant. Not review. Because even if something doesn't meet your expectations by a long shot it's still clickbait to rant about it and call it a review.

snippet.textDisplay:
I actually kinda liked Cats. It wasn't horrible, but the cast was amazing, I liked the music.
I didn't like how extremely cursed it was. The fur covering human hands and feet, that one scene where Taylor Swift got everybody high, also the Mice and Cockroaches, it was like watching a 2-hour long cursed image. I liked the music alright but at points found myself squirming uncomfortably, or squirming out of boredom.
On the other hand, I think Idris Elba did a really good job, I loved every one of those scenes he was in. I thought the train scene was fun, and throughout most of this the choreography was amazing, which is to be expected because the guy who directed this choreography also directed the choreography for Hamilton.

Overall, I give it a 5/10. It wasn't great but it was okay, and interesting enough that I'd sit through it again.

snippet.textDisplay:
Few things

1. It took me until 2:36 to realize that you were using a green screen for the background

2. The person who decided that this was a great musical for a live action movie was a complete and utter idiot. The majority of the theater community hates cats and would only see it for the costumes, which were fantastic for the broadway and tour productions. With this you don’t get the costumes so it’s incredibly hard to enjoy.

3. The plot in very unclear. ALW got the idea for the musical from some weird poetry book and one of them didn’t quite “fit” and was pretty confusing to understand. This is why it doesn’t make sense. The composer legit didn’t know wth was going on.

4. ALW came out with two musicals that year so one of them was bound to suck, in this case it was cats.

ALW- Andrew Lloyd Webber (big broadway composer, wrote Cats along with many broadway classics)

Feel free to correct me if anything’s incorrect
